## Representing Sinusoids via Complex Exponentials

**Euler**
$$e^{j\theta}=\cos\theta+j\sin\theta$$

**Graphically, plotted with the unit circle**
(figure)
- Fixed value of theta
- Results in an unexpected triangle

## Complex Amplitude

To get a general sinusoid, change from 1 to the <u>complex amplitude</u>
$$z=re^{j\theta}=A\cos\theta+jA\sin\theta$$
Theta is a function of time
$$\theta(t)=\omega t+\phi$$
Therefore…
$$z(t)=Ae^{j(\omega t+\phi)}=A\cos(\omega t + \phi)+jA\sin(\omega t+\phi)$$
*Note real component of z(t) looks familiar*


**Important**
- Starting vector * frequency 
- $z(t)=Ae^{j\phi}e^{j\omega t}$

## Exercise

## Sum of Sinusoids?

 
The sum is not as obvious. The sum is also a sinusoid, of the same frequency

### Key Result

### Why?

## Phasor addition rule
$$\sum\limits_iA_i\cos(\omega t+\phi_i)=\sum\limits\Re\{z_i(t)\}$$
$$z_i=A_ie^{j\phi_i}e^{j\omega t}$$
$$\Re\set{\sum\limits_iz_i}\qquad\rightarrow\qquad\sum\limits_iz_i=(\sum\limits_iA_ie^{j\phi_i})e^{j\omega t}$$
We know: $\Re\set{z_1+z_2}=\Re\set{z_1}+\Re\set{z_2}$
- Vector addition

Important condition: All sinusoids must have the same frequency
